Secondly, A Column about Racism in America, and Respect from the New York Times (last home of liberalism), that you might want to think about, esp. in light of Bill Clinton wanting us to &quot;come together&quot; (and after the O.J.Simpson Jury did just the opposite).  Check this &quot;abridged&quot; (it was too long so I cut it down a bit) column from the 6-16-97 NY Times:<br>
IN AMERICA / By BOB HERBERT - The Respect Divide<br><br>
Corey Arthur made virtually no effort to conceal his role in the murder of  Jonathan Levin (Dedicated Ghetto School teacher, son of Time Magazine's CEO), investigators said. Detectives believe that Mr. Arthur, 19 years old, bounced around on the subways in the day or two before Mr. Levin's death, trying to persuade first one and then another acquaintance to join him in the fatal scheme. <br><br>
After the widely admired 31-year-old high school teacher had been stabbed, shot and robbed in his upper West Side apartment, Mr. Arthur, like so many other young violent offenders, could hardly wait to tell friends what he had<br>
done, police said.  &quot;He was boasting about it,&quot; said a veteran homicide detective. &quot;They all do it.  They want their peers to know.&quot; <br><br>
Some people hit game-winning jump shots at the buzzer. Some save lives on the  operating table. Some write hit songs. It doesn't matter what they do. It's all about respect. They want their peers to know. <br><br>
They are obsessed with gaining respect. Unable to achieve it in more conventional ways, many turn to violence. A Brooklyn teen-ager once said to me, &quot;Nobody disses you when you've got a gun on 'em.&quot; <br><br>
Corey Arthur  had very little going for him. He wanted to be a rap star but  his  talent was limited. He had a police record.  He had a drug habit. An acquaintance quoted in a Times story said: &quot;He always wanted  to  have money but never wanted to get a job. His M.O. was to stick black <br>
people up or whoever he can.&quot; <br><br>
Mr. Arthur may not have known that Jonathan Levin had come from an  extremely wealthy family, but it's a safe bet that he envied what he saw as  his ex-teacher's exalted status. Jonathan Levin got lots of respect, Corey Arthur got none. <br><br>
Whatever happens to Mr. Arthur (the options range from <br>
acquittal to execution), it is in that deep and destructive divide that we need  to be working if  we want to prevent the many tragedies that flow from the  sense of worthlessness that is felt by so many potentially violent youngsters. <br><br>
It is the tallest of orders, and not at all for the faint of heart. Families have to be  knitted back together and fathers brought back into the home. Children have to  be taught to read and to reason in schools that are secure and in good repair.  Attitudes have to be changed so that violence loses its cachet and teen-agers don't feel that after killing someone they are entitled to turn around and take  a bow. Punishment for those who harm others should be swift and certain and severe. <br><br>
The demographers tell us a huge new wave of teen-agers is almost upon us. (Asian,Hispanic, Black, and White - me) We can engage them and guide their energy and talents along constructive paths. Or we can ignore them, and wait for the weakest and most desperate among them to seek their measure of respect and the applause of their peers by squeezing the trigger of a gun.&quot;<br><br>
Perhaps the draft of the 60's wasn't so bad afterall, did it delay the Bloods and the Crips for a later generation? Is the &quot;new&quot; sense of Black &quot;in your white face&quot; Rage related to Viet Nam?  I think so, I just think the connections are not so obvious. Is White &quot;payback&quot; the answer to Black Rage? Will this spill over into Asian communities, or do they just keep their heads down, and their kids in universities?   <br><br>
